<subSubSection id="0539BC47F496F1565D20C3ECA3F615DA" pageId="11" pageNumber="152" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="473CABB174509F1D5B45BC41E7995E17" pageId="11" pageNumber="152">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A6A39A168FF3811C290543A6CE5ABD74" pageId="11" pageNumber="152">
This species is easily distinguishable from other Nearctic 
<taxonomicName id="5ECB7179D4893657A09FA63CA376FE89" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Placusa" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Placusa" order="Coleoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="152" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Placusa</taxonomicName>
by its uniformly black to rarely dark brown body, long elytra (Fig. 52), and the shape of the genital structures (Figs 53-59). For a detailed description, see 
<bibRefCitation id="0213F7DAA3221CDC07C64362E67DD98C" author="Klimaszewski, J" journalOrPublisher="The Canadian Entomologist" pageId="15" pageNumber="156" pagination="1 - 47" title="Diversity of Placusa (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae, Aleocharinae) in Canada, with descriptions of two new species." url="10.4039/Ent1331-1" volume="133" year="2001">Klimaszewski et al. (2001)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<caption id="C7AA8DF05FFEC6798392E358F33D651D" pageId="11" pageNumber="152">
<paragraph id="68495BF205F5EBAD196E550DD31C44A4" pageId="11" pageNumber="152">
