<subSubSection id="CAE2F5FDC1C275B3C30C6B69936B22DD" lastPageId="12" lastPageNumber="153" pageId="11" pageNumber="152" type="natural history">
<paragraph id="3B65EB276D02A3C435CC10001571D099" pageId="11" pageNumber="152">Natural history.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3B3BD2451C373218766A07917DF56AA5" lastPageId="12" lastPageNumber="153" pageId="11" pageNumber="152">
Very little is known about the life history of this species. Adults in Quebec were captured in coniferous forests and mainly trapped in Lingren funnel traps (
<bibRefCitation id="953B2B99EBA18E7B6D297D24F2BED51B" author="Klimaszewski, J" journalOrPublisher="The Canadian Entomologist" pageId="15" pageNumber="156" pagination="1 - 47" title="Diversity of Placusa (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae, Aleocharinae) in Canada, with descriptions of two new species." url="10.4039/Ent1331-1" volume="133" year="2001">Klimaszewski et al. 2001</bibRefCitation>
). The Alberta specimens were captured in a window- 
<pageBreakToken id="E5490A73EF2D627AB692A0B5618E8288" pageId="12" pageNumber="153" start="start">traps</pageBreakToken>
attached to aspen snag in boreal aspen stands burned two years previously. Adults were collected in Alberta in August and elsewhere in June and August (
<bibRefCitation id="2973B252FF4296211601301E937B1C83" author="Seevers, CH" journalOrPublisher="Fieldiana Zoology" pageId="16" pageNumber="157" pagination="655 - 762" title="A revision of the North American and European staphylinid beetles of the subtribe Gyrophaenae (Aleocharinae, Bolitocharini)." url="10.5962/bhl.title.2816" volume="32" year="1951">Seevers 1951</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="122E01CF92F5B8BCE7DB423C163ACED5" pageId="12" pageNumber="153" type="comments">
<paragraph id="22BDA443C89C5895C45E6D5D3C3CDE1B" pageId="12" pageNumber="153">Comments.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F2B64339FDC612C0C420A1EFB4C272EE" pageId="12" pageNumber="153">This species is likely continuously distributed from Nova Scotia to British Columbia in northern boreal forest.</paragraph>
